Shrink polymers comprise well-developed soft materials for wrinkle manufacturing. The wavelength and amplitude of wrinkles produced by shrink polymers are predictable and controllable. Jan Groenewold64 proposed a basic model to describe the formation of biaxial and uniaxial wrinkles compatible with shrink polymers, as shown in Fig. 3a–c. The relationship between the wrinkle wavelength (λ) and the stiff-skin layer thickness (h) was derived from the uniaxial model under the condition of total free energy minimization, as expressed in Eq. 2. In the equation, η is proportional to the Young’s modulus ratio between the skin and the substrate. This model provides a basic principle to tune the wrinkle wavelength by controlling the skin layer thickness and Young’s modulus.2λ=2πη1/3h\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
